sentence-detokenized: FOOTBALL - LUCKY VICTORY FOR JAPAN, SURPRISE DEFEAT FOR CHINA.
Japan began their defence of the Asian Cup title with a fortunate 2-1 victory over Syria in a Group C league match on Friday.
But China saw their luck desert them in the second match of the group, falling by surprise 2-0 against newcomers Uzbekistan.

China controlled most of the match and squandered several chances until the 78th minute, when Uzbek striker Igor Shkvyrin took advantage of an erroneous header by the defence to slip the ball into a lob that went over the advancing Chinese goalkeeper and into an empty net.
Oleg Shatskiku secured victory in extra time with an unstoppable left-footed shot from just outside the box.
The former Soviet republic was playing in an Asian Cup final for the first time.
Despite winning the Asian Games title two years ago, Uzbekistan comes into the final as an outsider.
Two goals resulting from defensive errors in the last six minutes allowed Japan to come back and collect all three points in the opening encounter with Syria.

Takuya Takagi scored the winning goal in the 88th minute, heading a Hiroshige Yanagimoto cross towards the Syrian goal that goalkeeper Salem Bitar appeared to have covered but then let slide into the net.
It was Syria's second costly mistake in four minutes.
In the 84th minute, defender Hassan Abbas went up to intercept a long ball in the box, but only managed to deflect it into the top corner of Bitar's goal.
Nader Jokhadar put Syria ahead with a well-struck header in the seventh minute.
Japan then besieged the Syrian penalty area for much of the match, but rarely broke through the Syrian defence.
Bitar made excellent saves each time they did so.
Japan coach Shu Kamo said: 'The Syrian own goal turned out to be lucky for us.
The Syrians scored early and then played defensively, adopting long balls that put us in trouble. '
Japan, co-host of the World Cup in 2002 and ranked 20th in the world by FIFA, is the favourite to regain the title.
The United Arab Emirates host Kuwait and South Korea faces Indonesia on Saturday in Group A matches.
All four teams are tied with one point each from one match.
RUGBY UNION - CUTTITTA RETURNS TO ITALY AFTER ONE YEAR
Friday for the friendly against Scotland at Murrayfield, more than a year after the 30-year-old winger announced his retirement following disagreements over selection.
Cuttitta, who coach George Coste said he was certain to play on Saturday, was named in a 21-man squad missing only two from the team beaten 54-21 by England at Twickenham last month.
Stefano Bordon is out sick and Coste said he had ruled out full-back Corrado Covi, who had been recalled for the England game after five years away from the national team.
Cuttitta announced his retirement after the 1995 World Cup, where he complained about being excluded from the Italian team that faced England in the group stage.
Coste stated that he had contacted the player two months ago about a return.
"He ended the World Cup on a wrong note," said Coste.
"I thought it would be good to have him back and he told me he would be available.
I think the time is right for his return. "

FOOTBALL - LATE GOALS GIVE JAPAN VICTORY OVER SYRIA.
Two goals in the last six minutes gave Asian Cup holder Japan an uninspiring 2-1 victory over Syria on Friday.
Takuya Takagi scored a header in the 88th minute of the Group C match, after goalkeeper Salem Bitar had ruined an error-free performance by letting the ball slip under his body.
It was the second Syrian defensive error in four minutes.
In the 84th minute, defender Hassan Abbas went up to intercept a long ball in the box, but only managed to deflect it into the top corner of Bitar's goal.
Syria took the lead in the first serious attack in the seventh minute.
Nader Jokhadar headed a cross from the right by Ammar Awad into the top right corner of Kenichi Shimokawa's goal.
Japan then besieged the Syrian penalty area and had a goal disallowed for offside in the 16th minute.
A minute later, Bitar made a double save, first on Kazuyoshi Miura's header and then on Takagi's follow-up shot.
In the 37th minute, Bitar saved again from Miura, parrying his header from a corner.
Japan started the second half brightly, but Bitar denied them an equaliser when he dived to his right to save Naoki Soma's low shot in the 53rd minute.

Dutch striker Reggie Blinker had his indefinite suspension lifted by FIFA last Friday and is set to make his return for Sheffield Wednesday against Liverpool on Saturday.
Blinker missed his club's last two matches after FIFA handed him a worldwide ban for signing contracts with Wednesday and Udinese while playing for Feyenoord.
FIFA's player status commission, meeting in Barcelona, decided that although Udinese's document was essentially valid, it could not be legally protected.
The committee stated that the Italian club violated the rules by not informing Feyenoord, with whom the player was under contract.
Blinker was fined 75,000 Swiss francs ($57,600) for failing to inform the English club of his previous engagement with Udinese.
FOOTBALL - LEEDS 'BOWYER FINED FOR GETTING INTO FAST-FOOD FIGHT'.
Leeds' England Under-21 striker Lee Bowyer was fined last Friday for hurling chairs at restaurant staff during a brawl at a McDonald's fast-food restaurant.
Bowyer, 19, caught on security cameras, pleaded guilty to assault in a London court.
He was fined and ordered to pay a total of £175 to two members of staff who were injured in a fight at an east London restaurant in October.
Leeds had already fined Bowyer £4,000 ($6,600) and warned him that a repetition of his criminal behaviour could cost him his place in the team.
Bowyer, who moved to the Yorkshire club in August for £3.5m ($5.8m), was due to play against Middlesbrough on Saturday.

Centre Jason Little will miss Australia's end-of-tour game against the Barbarians at Twickenham on Saturday.
Little chose not to risk aggravating the knee injury that had ruled him out for much of the tour and was replaced by fellow Queenslander Daniel Herbert.
Owen Finegan recovered from the blows suffered in last weekend's test against Wales and retains his place in the back line ahead of Daniel Manu.

The Wallabies are aiming for their 13th consecutive win to end their European tour with a 100 per cent record, but they also want to turn on the style and give David Campese a fitting farewell in his last game in Australian colours.
At the moment the Wallabies have no special presentation planned for the 34-year-old winger, but an audience of 75,000 will still gather in the hope of witnessing one last moment of magic.
Campese will be facing a familiar opponent, Barbarians captain Rob Andrew, the man who brought down Australia with a last-gasp drop-goal in the World Cup quarter-final in Cape Town.
"Campo has a big following in this country and has had the public with him since he first played here in 1984," said Andrew, who is likely to make his last appearance at Twickenham.
On tour, Australia won all four Tests against Italy, Scotland, Ireland and Wales, scoring 414 points at an average of almost 35 points per game.

Championship commitments have limited the Barbarians' selection options, who still boast 13 international players, including England full-back Tim Stimpson and winger Tony Underwood, as well as All Black forwards Ian Jones and Norm Hewitt.

FOOTBALL - NON-SELECTED PLAYERS CALLED UP TO FACE MACEDONIA
Romania coach Anghel Iordanescu on Friday called up three players not selected in his team that will face Macedonia next week in a World Cup qualifying match.

Midfielder Valentin Stefan and striker Viorel Ion from Otelul Galati and defender Liviu Ciobotariu from National Bucharest are the newcomers for the European round of 16 match in Macedonia on 14 December.
Iordanescu said he chose them because of their good performances in the national championship, which sees National Bucharest in the lead and Otelul Galati in third. "
I think it is right to give them a chance,' he told reporters.
Steaua Bucharest, holders of the league title and finished bottom of their Champions League group in the European Cup, have only two players in their squad.
Attacking midfielder Adrian Ilie, recently transferred from Steaua to Turkish club Galatasaray, is out after two yellow cards.

CRICKET - LARA ENDURES ANOTHER UNHAPPY DAY.
Australia gave Brian Lara another reason to be unhappy when he beat the West Indies by five wickets in the opening game of the World Series limited overs on Friday.
Lara, sanctioned on Wednesday for misconduct, was sent off five times, extending a disappointing run of results on tour.
Australia, leading 2-0 in the five-match series, topped the West Indies' total of 172 with eight balls to spare, ending a run of six consecutive one-day defeats.
All-rounder Greg Blewett guided his team to a comfortable victory with an unbeaten 57 in 90 balls, to the delight of the 42,442 spectators.
Man-of-the-match Blewett came to the wicket with a total of 70 for two and struck three fours during a trouble-free innings that lasted 129 minutes.
His crucial fifth-round partnership with fellow all-rounder Stuart Law, who scored 21 points, added 71 points on 85 balls.
Lara looked bewildered during his brief stay on the bench, before making a simple catch at Shane Warne in midfield.
West Indies tour manager Clive Lloyd apologised for Lara's behaviour on Tuesday.
Lara had told Australia coach Geoff Marsh that wicketkeeper Ian Healy was not welcome in the visitors' dressing room.
The Melbourne public was clearly angered by the incident, and loudly insulted the West Indies vice-captain as he walked towards the centre.
It fell to left-hander Shivnarine Chanderpaul to hold the innings together with a gritty 54, despite the handicap of a groin injury.
Chanderpaul was forced to rely on a runner for most of his innings after he was injured while running back to his box to avoid being struck out.
Pakistan, which will arrive in Australia later this month, is the other team participating in the World Series tournament.

CRICKET - LARA SUFFERS FURTHER HARDSHIP DURING THE AUSTRALIAN TOUR.

West Indies batsman Brian Lara suffered another blow to his Australian tour, having already been sanctioned for misconduct when he was dismissed cheaply in the first game of limited overs against Australia on Friday.
Lara, who earned a stern rebuke from his own tour management after an angry outburst against Australian wicketkeeper Ian Healy, scored five runs to prolong a phase of poor form with the bat.
The West Indies vice-captain struggled to find time during his 36 minutes at the base, before chipping a ball from halfback Tom Moody straight to Shane Warne at midfield.
West Indies were 53-2 in 15 overs when rain halted play at the Melbourne Cricket Ground after captain Courtney Walsh won the toss and elected to bat.
Lara's outburst three days ago clearly turned part of the Australian public against him.
On his way to the wicket, he was greeted by loud booing from the audience.
On several occasions during his innings, the crowd joined in a series of obscene chants against him.
Tour manager Clive Lloyd apologised on Wednesday for Lara's behaviour when he confronted Australia coach Geoff Marsh in the opposition dressing room to protest his dismissal in Tuesday's second Test.
Lloyd did not say what form the discipline would take.

Lara, who holds the record for the highest score in Test and first-class cricket, said he was unhappy with Healy's role in the incident and questioned whether the ball had reached Australia's goalkeeper.
Australia won the match at the Sydney Cricket Ground by 124 runs and took a two-nil lead in the five-Test series after Lara failed in both innings.
Lara has not yet marked a century since the West Indies arrived in Australia five weeks ago.
Both the West Indies and Australian leadership downplayed the incident, emphasising that relations between the two parties were not adversely affected.
Pakistan, which will arrive next week, is the third team in the triangular World Series tournament.
